# Gogo Queue Worker Rules

Use this rule when adding background jobs, worker commands, beat schedules,
retries, timeouts, result handling, or canvas workflows.

Framework module: `github.com/cybersaksham/gogo`.

## Tasks

- Register tasks in app `tasks.go` files with the public Gogo queue APIs.
- Name tasks with an app namespace, such as `<app>.<task>`.
- Keep task payloads small, serializable, and stable.
- Keep task business logic in services so HTTP/API/admin paths can share it.
- Queue task coverage includes task registration, task options, signatures,
  kwargs, headers, envelopes, JSON/raw/gob serialization, compression,
  trusted serializer checks, routing, priorities, countdown, ETA, expiration,
  results, events, inspection, security signing, and admin metadata.

## Brokers And Results

- Configure brokers with `GOGO_BROKER_URL`.
- Configure result backends with `GOGO_RESULT_BACKEND` only when task results
  are required.
- Supported queue integrations include in-memory/local behavior for tests and
  Redis/RabbitMQ/SQL-backed integrations where configured.
- Broker packages include shared broker interfaces, Redis broker integration,
  and RabbitMQ broker integration. Result backend packages include shared
  backend interfaces, Redis results, SQL results, and memory/local test
  behavior.

## Reliability

- Set retries, retry delay/backoff, timeout, expiration, routing key, queue,
  acknowledgement behavior, and idempotency expectations explicitly for
  production tasks.
- Worker coverage includes solo, goroutine, and process-pool strategy hooks,
  concurrency, prefetch, acknowledgement policy, retries, hard and soft
  timeouts, rate limits, cancellation, result storage, and error reporting.
- Design tasks to be safe on retry. Use idempotency keys or database guards for
  side effects.
- Do not put secrets in queue payloads or task names.
- Capture errors in logs/observability and expose worker inspection where
  needed.

## Scheduling And Canvas

- Use beat schedules for periodic jobs.
- Use chains, groups, chords, and other canvas workflows when task ordering or
  fan-out/fan-in matters.
- Beat schedule coverage includes interval, crontab, clocked, and solar-style
  schedule metadata plus schedule stores and locks.
- Canvas coverage includes chains, groups, chords, chunks, maps, workflow
  serialization, and fan-out/fan-in result coordination.
- Keep schedule definitions close to app task registration unless they are
  project-level operations.

## Commands

```bash
gogo worker
gogo beat
gogo inspect
gogo queues
```
